<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Health Select Committee_x000b_House of Commons</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from 4Children (PEX 0010)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4Children is the national charity all about children and families. We have spearheaded a joined-up, integrated approach to children’s services and work with a wide range of partners around the country to ensure children and families have access to the services and support they need in their communities. We run Sure Start Children’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Centres</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> as well as family and youth services across Britain.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4Children develops, influences and shapes national policy on all aspects of the lives of children, young people and families. Consequently, we take a particular interest in those aspects of policy with implications for parents and children. As the Government’s strategic partner for early years and childcare through The Children’s Partnership, we represent the sector’s views and experiences. We also work to put the needs of children and families firmly on the political and policy agenda.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4Children welcomes the opportunity to respond to the Health Select Committee consultation on Public Expenditure on Health and Social Care. Our response focuses on the question of “progress on the integration of health services with social care and other services”, and specifically how this relates to children and families. In our response, we draw upon our extensive knowledge and experience as a provider of children’s services, including through running over 80 Children’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Centres</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. We also draw on other research we have undertaken to support our policy and advocacy work, including our 2013 Census of Children’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Centres</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (published on 29 October 2013)</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, the only</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">national annual survey of Children’s Centre activities. The Census poses a number of questions about the provision of health services through </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">Centres</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> and about integration with wider NHS health service provision.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Children’s Centre are defined (by the Department for Education</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">) as “a place or a group of places: which is managed by or on behalf of, or under arrangements with, the local authority with a view to securing that early childhood services in the local authority are made available in an integrated way.”  They have been designed with a specified core purpose to “improve outcomes for young children and their families and reduce inequalities between families in the greatest need and their peers”, including in child and family health and life chances. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4Children’s Children’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Centres</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Census 2013 found that</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Centres</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> are supporting growing numbers of families and children, despite the undercurrent threat of budget cuts. Nearly three-quarters of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Centres</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> reported increasing demand, with the survey suggesting that for the first time, more than one million families were being supported, including two-thirds of the most vulnerable families with a child aged 0-5 years. It also found that Children’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Centres</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> were working with a wider range of agencies – including in the health sector and that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Centres</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> were viewed as having an increasingly important role in delivery of services.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Bringing together services and co-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ordinating</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> support around the needs of children and families is at the heart of Children’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Centres’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> delivery. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Excellent working partnerships with local services are crucial, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">particularly in the health arena, if we are to see the sort of “holistic” offering vital to improving outcomes for children and families through intervening at early stages of their development. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4Children works closely with healthcare professionals, including health visitors and midwives, as a matter of routine. However, nationally there </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">has been mixed success in terms </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">of partnership working, resulting in a continued and unacceptable duplication of effort. There is much more that can be done to be more efficient with the money available and take advantage of opportunities to reduce spending waste. Children’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Centres</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> must be at the heart of an early intervention and prevention strategy, demanding a joined-up approach. Finding ways to drive greater integration in the provision of local services is essential to their success, with a “rewiring” of public services (as called for by the Local Government Association</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">) needed in several areas.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In order to examine the degree to which </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Centres</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and health service providers are currently working together, respondents to the 4Children Children’s Centre Census 2013 were asked what services they were working in partnership with their local health service to provide. Health visitor clinics were cited by 81% of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Centres</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (perhaps reflecting the substantial emphasis that is being placed on partnership with Children’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Centres</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in the health visitor implementation </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">), while 79% of respondents said they were providing baby weighing services in partnership with their local health service.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Substantial numbers of Children’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Centres</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> also said that they were working with local health services to provide ante-natal services, with 64% offering ante-natal midwifery clinics and 47% offering antenatal classes. 43% said they provided post-natal midwifery clinics. These results are broadly consistent with findings from the Department for Education’s “Evaluation of Children’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Centres</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in England” (ECCE)</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> A recent ECCE report into the delivery of family services in Children’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Centres</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (interviewing 121 Centre Managers) found  that around 64% of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Centres</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> provided ante-natal services (with 97% of these doing so in partnership with other agencies), while around 48% delivered post-natal classes (88% in partnership with others).</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4Children recommends that local authorities and Health and Wellbeing boards put Children’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Centres</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> at the heart of their early intervention and preventative strategies. Doing so will enhance outcomes for children and families and bring economic and social benefits for our society and wider communities by improving the circumstances of troubled and vulnerable families. As the latest regulations set out, all service providers should work to ensure that Children’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Centres</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> occupy a central position in the delivery of the Healthy Child </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, as well as have access to a named health visitor. Resources provided to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Centres</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> from local authorities should be tailored to reflect this and to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">maximise</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the savings that can be achieved by integrated working. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">4Children also recommends further integration of local services into Children’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Centres</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to establish and deliver a “holistic” whole family model of support, including by those in the health sector (such as health visitors and community midwives), as well as in other areas including social workers, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Jobcentre</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Plus and the police. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">To help this integrated approach succeed, 4Children also believes there should also be a statutory requirement for data and information sharing between local authorities, agencies and Children’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Centres</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. Children’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Centres</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> do not currently have access to a wide range of data, from local authorities, health providers and live birth data from the health service. This data would potentially assist and support </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Centres’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> own work, including in identifying the whereabouts of children or families in need (including vulnerable families); and around early intervention and Troubled Families. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">4Children (2013) Children’s Centre Census 2013 </span><a href="http://www.4children.org.uk/Resources/Detail/Children-Centre-Census-2013"><span style="color:#0000cc; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:underline">http://www.4children.org.uk/Resources/Detail/Children-Centre-Census-2013</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> The Department for Education (2013) Sure Start children’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">centres</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> statutory guidance </span><a href="http://media.education.gov.uk/assets/files/pdf/s/childrens%20centre%20stat%20guidance%20april%202013.pdf"><span style="color:#0000cc; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:underline">http://media.education.gov.uk/assets/files/pdf/s/childrens%20centre%20stat%20guidance%20april%202013.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">Local Government Association</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><a href="http://www.local.gov.uk/campaigns"><span style="color:#0000cc; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:underline">http://www.local.gov.uk/campaigns</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> Department for Education (2013) Evaluation of Children’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">Centres</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> in England (ECCE) Strand 3 </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/evaluation-of-childrens-centres-in-england-strand-3-delivery-of-family-services-by-childrens-centres"><span style="color:#0000cc; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:underline">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/evaluation-of-childrens-centres-in-england-strand-3-delivery-of-family-services-by-childrens-centres</span></a></p></body></html>